{"product_id": "208480", "page": 45, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-05-29", "text": "i probably would like this game, but with my current rig i can't run it at 60fps, when i get to boston it drops frames massively, i can run black flag and rogue at max 60 fps np, i run unity with everything ultra except AA and the nvidea HBAO+, i run it on SSAO and i get like 70 fps, why this game runs so bad i don't know, i would like to play it, but for me it's unplayable, i would like to get into the story though, since the game has connor witch is on of Haythan and grandson of Edward, 2 awesome characters!\nEdit: i've changed my statement, i'm now an owner of a GTX 1080 and this was one of the first games i've tried to play, for what i've played, i like it so far.", "hours": 25.0, "user_id": "76561198036138744", "username": "Definitly not a Sloth", "products": 448, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 45, "page_order": 4, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-05-28", "text": "I wanted to like this game, I really did. The frontier locations are beautiful the combat (especially on the ocean) is fun, but it's all brought down by incoherent and buggy gameplay. After playing this game nearly to completion I am certain that significant portions of it were simply never play-tested.\nMission design is schizophrenic even when not bugged, with a difficulty curve like a roller coaster. One missions is literally impossible to get full sync unless you keep reloading from a checkpoint until a target's pathing bugs out.\nMany locations have broken free-running pathing, and obvious intended paths or stealth approaches that are broken due to design errors and were clearly never tested in-game. Multiple naval missions have full sync requirement that punish you for upgrading your ship's weapons, as they require you to intentionally miss almost all your shots to avoid killing the targets outright before their weak points are exposed.\nOne sequence has three consecutive non-interactive cut-scenes, one after another, each of which can be skipped (jumping to a loading screen that takes longer than the cut-scene), followed immediately by a much longer, unskippable scene. It's so bad it must be intentional.\nAnother source of frustration is that the game is constantly taking temporary control of your camera, be it for looting a body, performing and execution, or showing you an incoming enemy ship. Every time it does this, the forced camera change lingers far longer than necessary, both annoying you and leaving you open to attacks in combat, or making it hard to navigate alleys or narrow ocean passages.\nAssassin's Creed 3: everywhere you look, something's broken.", "hours": 232.4, "username": "Stone Cold Jane Austen", "products": 235, "early_access": false}
