{"product_id": "208480", "page": 310, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-08-07", "text": "This game gets a lot of crap for being \"awful\". I would say that is an exaggeration. While the game doesn't always do a great job of explaining all of its mechanics, it is still highly enjoyable. The graphics are highly detailed, the sound is sufficient and the music is fitting given the time period the game takes place in. The combat is much improved from previous games in the series and the addition of ship sailing is a breath of fresh air for the series. If you are a fan of the series, this game likely won't disappoint too much. If you are new to the series, do yourself a favor and start elsewhere. Assassin's Creed 2 is a far more polished game and when combined with its direct sequels (Brotherhood and Revelations) makes a great story.", "hours": 43.7, "username": "pixeliminator", "products": 523, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 310, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-08-06", "text": "After spending 80+ hours with this game, I would say that yes, this is a great game.  There are a lot of conflicting opinions surrounding it, but I feel diving into both the side missions and the main story equally balances things out and presents Conor (the hero) as a more complete person and a complex and interesting one at that.\nMy suggestion for getting the most out of your experience is to take on the homestead side missions whenever they become available.  Not only are they needed for some of the upgades, they help flesh out Conor and provide more context for things going on back in Davenport while you're off tracking down Haythem.  They also seem key to keeping Conor seem like a total jackass amidst his heroics.", "hours": 83.1, "username": "Akmetan", "products": 331, "early_access": false}
