{"product_id": "208480", "page": 349, "page_order": 8, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-05-02", "text": "I was lucky I got this on Steam Sale.. Well I played through AC1 and AC2 and liked the idea of this one but it hurts.. hurts not in a good way.. pretty graphics and nice sound the preachy patrotism makes it feel like im stuck in a propaganda machine. I was going to play through this and then play AC4 but sod it its just not worth it so bring on the Priates!", "hours": 29.1, "username": "CalebAlpha", "products": 758, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 349, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-05-02", "text": "I recommend this game to a majority of people, not all. It has great looking graphics, senic enviroment. But the rough points it belittles Americans, Christianity, Butchers the charactor of George Wash. Sure it 'Exists' in an \"alternate reality.\", Also your character you play is sorta racist against whites and vise versa. I do recommend it for anyone who enjoys touring cities in the 1750-1800. it is true the desomond levels are sorta crappy but the Animus is almost always interesting it can be quite addictive but it can get alittle repetative", "hours": 80.4, "username": "wulfy mcwulfston", "products": 222, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 350, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-05-01", "text": "As a historian of colonial America and a fan of the Assassin's Creed series who thought the formula was getting a little stale, I was quite happy with this game.\nGraphics are great, colonial America has never looked so beautiful in a video game and the background historical events are accurate to an astonishing degree (just listen to the newspaper men yelling out the recent events from Britain). Gameplay has received minor updates that keep it amusing, the forests provide an interesting dynamic in the primarily urban Assassin's Creed universe. I found the main story OTT, and the gameplay eventually became repetitive and the rewards not so great. Ubisoft need to step it up in future games to keep my business coming. 8/10.", "hours": 57.6, "user_id": "76561198014056666", "username": "P\u00e8re Duchesne", "products": 227, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 350, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-05-01", "text": "Rather interesting, gorgeous landscape, many things to do, mostly good freedom openworld feeling.\nBUT, serious flaws that definitely prevent me from recommending this.\n- UPlay, and overall Ubisoft crap. Yeah, not that big of a deal, but constantly annoying.\n- Keyboard+mouse work... mostly. Untill you get stuck into a menu. Or it stops responding during a fight. or... well it's obviously not really been worked on. I guess I should use a controller... luckily enough I own one. But I hate using it, I'm not confortable at all with it, and playing on a PC, I should be able to use PC-specific controllers, for christ sake.\n- Large chunks of the game are (barely) interactive cutscenes. For the introduction, allright, I can bear with it. But it goes on, and on, and on... entire missions are cutscenes disguised with quick-time-events and contextual gimmicks. Even out of the main plot, the free-form gameplay often feels like gimmicky minigames and is riddled with QTEs.\n- Same spirit for the \"simplified free-form high-profile running\", which is AC's signature: your character keeps trying to \"adapt\" to things you didn't ask for, bumping into corners, jumping for an assassination when you just intended to drop from a roof peacefully, climbing into an inclimbable (?) wall when you were trying to run away...\nOverall, a promising, but ultimately extremely frustrating and infuriating game. I'll probably give up on it.", "hours": 41.5, "user_id": "76561197991809463", "username": "Bleral", "products": 166, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 350, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-05-01", "text": "My first hands-on experience with the Assassin's Creed franchise. I was pleasantly surprised. It's a very visually and graphically appealing game and it runs extremely smooth. The combat mechanics are very fluid and numerous, which creates a very fun experience and many different playstyles. Running/Wallclimbing can be clunky at times, but it mostly works out.\nThe biggest drawback of this game is the story. It's very confusing and the ending is underwhelming and disappointing. However, the historical period is interesting and extremely well integrated. The cities, people, nature and overall feeling of the game are convincing and skillfully made. Most side-missions are great, but many feel repetitive. The DLC expansions are all worth the time and price and deliver a new experience.\nThe best part of this game has to be the naval combat. It's super fun and easy to understand - It's very understandable that the sequel to this game is focused around this. Assassin's Creed III has made me a fan of the franchise and I will definetely be playing the rest of the franchise after this experience.", "hours": 84.5, "username": "Jysk Senget\u00f8jslayer", "products": 261, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 350, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-04-30", "text": "Despite a lackluster story Assassin's Creed III remains true to the core gameplay of the franchise, and offers quite a few hours of entertainment for those familiar with the franchise.\nThe game as a whole doesn't really offer anything new gameplay-wise, but it does improve on a lot of the mechanics of the franchise.\nDespite its shortcomings, Assassin's Creed III offers a fun experience, but only when you look at it from a gameplay-perspective.", "hours": 1.5, "username": "The_Mechanic", "products": 290, "early_access": false}
