{"product_id": "208480", "page": 361, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-03-15", "text": "The best educational games are the ones that don't feel educational. In Assassin's Creed III you can fight the American War for Independence the sneaky way, meeting real historical leaders, discovering landmarks, and participating in significant events along the way. Every one of these you discover will earn you a humorous and informative entry in the game's encyclopedia, presumably written by one of the main characters. You can also read Ben Franklin's wise and witty proverbs in the various issues of Poor Richard's Almanac, if you're fast enough to catch the pages. For those of us who grew up in the 90's with Carmen Sandiego and the Clue Finders, the Assassin's Creed franchise definitely fills a void. Unlike most modern games, these are guaranteed to yield a return on invested time. Play slowly.", "hours": 45.1, "user_id": "76561198069677248", "username": "Woodfinch", "products": 866, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 361, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-03-15", "text": "Previously without having played Assassins Creed 3 I was being negative and quite biased when speaking of Assassins Creed series. It all changed upon meeting Connor, the main protagonist, of this entry. Now, I am absolutely positive that this is one of the best action games I have played in years. There are a few misfires that could jeopordize some aspects of the game, yet the good things undermine the significance of the not so good things.\nThe good thing is the relative freedom that's been given to the player in how he or she interacts with world. Not only you can explore vast cities of Boston and New York you have a whole wilderness in between them to explore. You can harvest, craft and even build your own village. And lets not forget about the sea battles, that are the absolute best of the game.\nThe story is also satisfying as is it's main subject - Connor. I am not a big fan of the animus thing as I would enjoy the game more if it was a Connor only game, but, hell, all stories need a plot machine.\nNow onto the not so good. Let's start with saying that some aspects of the game feel quite dated. The auto run is not good as Connor in times could get stuck in numerous cluster scattered around as well as jump onto the wall you never intended to jump. That's annoying and I've been yelling at my computer at times in desperation.\nOverall, the game is fantastic, I do not regret neither the money nor the time spent on it.\n4.9/5", "hours": 43.5, "username": "Fen", "products": 504, "early_access": false}
