{"product_id": "208480", "page": 395, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-01-01", "text": "As much as I love the story and gameplay of the AC series, this one is riddled with glitches and errors. It detracted from the playing experience so much that I had to get up and walk away from the game midway through its most climactic events. I purchased the Season Pass and the game will not even let me use it, so there's another $15 down the drain for a game I do not want to play beyond the basic content anyway. It is just too frustrating!\nUbisoft needs to take more pride in their work and decide if they are trying to tell a compelling story and make a good game or just make a deadline.", "hours": 54.5, "username": "JRDN", "products": 108, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 395, "page_order": 2, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-01-01", "text": "I liked the first one because it was something new. I enjoyed the second one -- I guess because I wasn't sick of it yet? It fleshed out some mechanics, carried some improvements, and introduced a decent story, maybe that was enough. The sequels  to the second I accepted because they didn't have their own number.\nThis one finally did the trick though, I'm now disillusioned with this damn series. Its the same game in a new skin.", "hours": 9.1, "username": "Six", "products": 520, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 395, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-01-01", "text": "I fail to understand why AC3 has been getting so many negative reviews. Admittedly it may have something to do with me getting into it long after the final DLC and/or patch(es) came out, but a lot of the bad reviews I've been seeing have less to do with issues in the software and more with the game itself.\nI liked AC2 more than the first, Brotherhood more than AC2, Revelations more than Brotherhood... every single one has been nothing but an improvement upon the previous in nearly every way. This is no exception.\nThat doesn't mean I have no complaints myself. I still have the same complaints I did when I first started Brotherhood. The arbitrary camera \"helper angles,\" during certain dungeon missions, and certain scenes that are nigh impossible to finish - especially in the case of\n. I've also never been fond of requirements for \"full synchronisation.\" I find most of them tedious in the extreme, so I usually just ignore them. Static Collision Detection and how the \"parkour triggers\" are affected by it also still needs a lot of work. But, as suggested, little-to-none of that has anything to do with AC3 itself. It's just stuff that I don't care for, and a couple other things Ubisoft are still working on.\nAnd I gotta say, after those privateering missions, I can certainly see why Black Flag is such a success by comparison. I've always been fond of the concept of maritime naval warfare in gaming, but I would never have expected an Assassin's Creed game to fill that niche. I will certainly be getting AC4 \"Deluxe\" when I can.\nAnd now for one of those silly \"out of ten\" ratings: 9/10 (would be ten if not for\n, the most frustrating part of the entire game for me)\nA little apropos: I've seen a lot of complaints about AC devs and storywriters \"failing at historical accuracy\" and/or \"realism.\" Hey uh, guys? It's a\n,\na damned simulator intended for educational purposes. It even clearly states during startup that it is \"inspired by historical people and events.\" That's \"\n,\"\n\"based on.\" Seriously, stop it. It's embarrassing, just stop.\nOh and\n? Still a better ending than Mass Effect 3. Shameless plug, I know, but it doesn't make it any less true.\nAnyways, yes, I do indeed recommend this game. Wholeheartedly.", "hours": 122.5, "username": "zhaarteth", "products": 283, "early_access": false}
