{"product_id": "208480", "page": 404, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-12-23", "text": "Excellent story, nice setting and plenty of things to do. From killing redcoats, turning the tide of war, to naval combat and upgrades of your weapons and ship. Trading also plays a nice part of money making and there is a nice treasure search which ads to this game and makes it the best AC up to Black Flag. Recommended.", "hours": 162.2, "username": "Zenoslaf", "products": 1449, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 404, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-12-23", "text": "After frustration due to controls in the first 3 sequences, you even start to enjoy this game. And the further it gets, the better. With tasks ranging from simple freerunning to stearing a ship, you get to do pretty much everything imaginable for the period.\nSome tasks however are impossible and not worth your time, e.g., mini-games. Unless you enjoy all those antique board games, there are more convenient and faster ways of getting money, like looting soldiers or selling the hunt.\nAfter getting acquinted with the game (which might take quite a lot of time, if you haven't played AC before), it becomes a world you want to immerse in again and again.\nWith all the alternative history and action, this game is like a combination of Dan Brown's novel, parkour and Skyrim", "hours": 116.7, "username": "Dimitri Cosmos \u2705", "products": 291, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
