{"product_id": "208480", "page": 449, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-27", "text": "This one is a disappointment. I really wanted to enjoy the game, but the first half of it just has Haytham or Connor running from cutscene to cutscene to quicktime event back to cutscene.\nYahtzee's review is very accurate - the series has lost its focus and needs to get back to stabbing people. You can PLAY CHECKERS with people. Why do I want to do that? Naval battles are a ton of fun, but they're also not related to the plot at all.\nConnor isn't nearly as engaging as Ezio, and the voice acting is partially to blame for that. The missions seem to encourage one specific mode of attack rather than leaving the player to choose what to do.\nI really want to like this game, but it's just served me disappointment after disappointment. Stick with AC2 or Brotherhood. If you really want this, wait for the price to drop.", "hours": 36.1, "username": "KevinZDores", "products": 178, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "208480", "page": 449, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-27", "text": "I can't help thinking that a shark has been jumped somewhere... This isn't a bad game, and it isn't even the worst of the series.  But it sure isn't the best. It turns out that the American Frontier just isn't as engaging a world as the previous games. It turns out that our new protagonist is a boring sap. Worse, it turns out that the big overarching story has a pretty weak ending. Do I recommend it? Yeah, sure.  I guess. There's stuff to do in it. I've thrown 60 hours at it.  But I've got to be honest, some of those hours were a slog...  Once it drops below the $40 mark, I might pick it up, but the full price feels like a ripoff.  Oh, lastly, the moronic UPlay system is still there, but it has been somewhat defanged. It is now just annoying and stupid instead of actively evil.  So its got that going for it, at least.", "hours": 59.5, "username": "mdwyer", "products": 315, "early_access": false}
